<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="126" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,318,734,760]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Etymology</emphasis>
:—This new species is named after the Yanachaga Chemillén National Park where is found. Chemillén is a Yanesha word that means “burnt” and it refers to the aspect of the mountains of the region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,377,806,832]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Conservation Status</emphasis>
:— 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[412,649,806,832]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[412,649,806,832]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Miconia chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only known only from one population a at the border of the Yanachaga Chemillen National Park, in an area that is highly degraded and under logging pressure. Based on the paucity of collections it should be considered Data Deficient (DD), following the IUCN criteria (2001) as implemented by the IUCN guidelines (2011). However, based on its limited distribution and endangered habitat, we recommend that this species is considered Critically Endangered.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="126" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,315,986,1012]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Discussion</emphasis>
:—The anthers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[513,749,986,1012]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[513,749,986,1012]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Miconia chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a slender but prolonged connective with apically widening thecae that open by broad pores. These characteristics place this new species in the traditional definition of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Richard ex de Candolle 1828: 180) Triana ex Hook." authorityName="Triana ex Hook." baseAuthorityName="Richard ex de Candolle" baseAuthorityPageNumber="180" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Hypoxanthus">
<emphasis box="[1358,1451,1023,1048]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Miconia</emphasis>
section 
<emphasis box="[223,371,1058,1084]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Hypoxanthus</emphasis>
(Richard ex 
<bibRefCitation author="de Candolle, A. P." box="[517,773,1058,1084]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" refId="ref8429" refString="de Candolle, A. P. (1828) Memoires sur la famille des Melastomacees. Treuttel et Wurtz, Paris, 82 pp." type="book" year="1828">de Candolle 1828: 180</bibRefCitation>
) Triana ex Hook.
</taxonomicName>
f., in Bentham &amp; Hooker (1867: 764), also known as 
<emphasis box="[255,278,1095,1120]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M</emphasis>
. section 
<taxonomicName authority="(Crueger 1847: 111) Triana ex Hook." authorityName="Hook." baseAuthorityName="Crueger" baseAuthorityPageNumber="111" baseAuthorityYear="1847" box="[384,994,1094,1121]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Glossocentrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[384,554,1094,1120]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Glossocentrum</emphasis>
(Crueger 1847: 111) Triana ex Hook.
</taxonomicName>
f. in Bentham &amp; Hook (1867: 763); see 
<bibRefCitation author="Goldenberg, R." box="[136,356,1130,1156]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" refId="ref8628" refString="Goldenberg, R. (2000) O Genero Miconia Ruiz &amp; Pav. (Melastomataceae): I. Listagens analiticas, II. Revisao Taxonomica da Secao Hypoxanthus (Rich. ex DC.) Hook. F. Ph. D. Instituto de Biologia, Universidade Estadual de Campinas, Campinas, 249 pp." type="book" year="2000">Goldenberg (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. The great majority of the species in this group are from Eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1120,1188,1130,1156]" name="Brazil" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Brazil</collectingCountry>
but eleven species are known from 
<collectingCountry box="[281,336,1167,1193]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Peru</collectingCountry>
. The members of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Triana ex Hook." baseAuthorityName="Richard ex de Candolle" baseAuthorityYear="1828" box="[538,873,1166,1192]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Hypoxanthus">
<emphasis box="[538,631,1167,1192]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Miconia</emphasis>
section 
<emphasis box="[725,873,1166,1192]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Hypoxanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[909,960,1167,1193]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Peru</collectingCountry>
are mostly found below 
<quantity box="[1241,1313,1166,1193]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" unit="m" value="800.0">800 m</quantity>
elevation in Amazonian forests, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[427,602,1202,1228]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[427,602,1202,1228]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in cloud forests ca. 
<quantity box="[980,1064,1202,1229]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" unit="m" value="2500.0">2500 m</quantity>
elevation. Molecular phylogenetic work is necessary to ascertain whether this species is indeed closely related to the Brazilian species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Triana ex Hook." baseAuthorityName="Richard ex de Candolle" baseAuthorityYear="1828" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Hypoxanthus">
<emphasis box="[1272,1365,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Miconia</emphasis>
section 
<emphasis box="[136,284,1274,1300]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Hypoxanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[136,1452,158,1517]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">
The flowers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[358,533,1310,1336]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[358,533,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resemble those of 
<taxonomicName authority="Gleason (1936: 535)" authorityName="Gleason" authorityPageNumber="535" authorityYear="1936" box="[826,1227,1310,1337]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="semisterilis">
<emphasis box="[826,991,1310,1336]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. semisterilis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gleason, H. A." box="[996,1227,1310,1337]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" pagination="533 - 537" refId="ref8591" refString="Gleason, H. A. (1936) Seven American Melastomes. Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club 63: 533 - 537. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 2480934" type="journal article" year="1936">Gleason (1936: 535)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, especially in calyx, style and anther shape. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[510,685,1346,1372]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[510,685,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has dimorphic anthers (as opposed to isomorphic in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1936" box="[1271,1435,1346,1372]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="semisterilis">
<emphasis box="[1271,1435,1346,1372]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. semisterilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and 5-merous flowers (vs. 4-merous). Additionally, the inflorescence of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" box="[958,1135,1382,1408]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis box="[958,1135,1382,1408]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is glomerulate (flowers not clustered in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1936" box="[278,446,1418,1444]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="semisterilis">
<emphasis box="[278,446,1418,1444]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. semisterilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the leaves are glabrous abaxially (vs. densely stellate-pubescent). Vegetatively 
<taxonomicName authorityName="L. A. Cardenas" authorityYear="2014" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chemillensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. chemillensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Gleason (1931: 240)" authorityName="Gleason" authorityPageNumber="240" authorityYear="1931" box="[405,754,1454,1480]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="klugii">
<emphasis box="[405,509,1454,1480]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. klugii</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Gleason, H. A." box="[518,754,1454,1480]" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" pagination="215 - 262" refId="ref8518" refString="Gleason, H. A. (1931) Studies on the flora of northern South America-XV. Recent collections of Melastomataceae from Peru and Amazonian Brazil. Bulletin of the Torrey Botanical Club 58: 215 - 262. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.2307 / 2480704" type="journal article" year="1931">Gleason (1931: 240)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, also from 
<collectingCountry box="[888,942,1455,1481]" name="Peru" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">Peru</collectingCountry>
, but differs in leaf pubescence (glabrous vs. densely stellate) and the anthers of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gleason" authorityYear="1931" box="[531,632,1490,1516]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Melastomataceae" genus="Miconia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="5" pageNumber="126" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="klugii">
<emphasis box="[531,632,1490,1516]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="126">M. klugii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lack the connective below the fertile portion of the thecae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
